5/1/2025, 12:18:39 PM,Snowflake,noreply@snowflake.com,NA,aicoaching2025@gmail.com,noreply@snowflake.com,Snowflake Notification: Introducing User-Based Access Control (UBAC) for Streamlined Sharing of Development Assets in Snowflake,<760079685.95763303.1746116319231@abmktmail-batch1f.marketo.org>,"Dear Candace,
Snowflake is sending you this important message regarding an upcoming behavior change that may impact your account.  Please read below for more details:

In the 2025_02 Bundle <https://go.snowflake.net/MjUyLVJGTy0yMjcAAAGaK51H_AhYmSr9hGgjoAn8dgK5RCX2-6_66kx9GWjffFmrxgv6hfb4-jXPxACVMIx3hVWgxW0=>, which is expected to be enabled by default the week of May 4, 2025 in release 9.12 (dates subject to change), Snowflake announced BCR-1924 <https://go.snowflake.net/MjUyLVJGTy0yMjcAAAGaK51H_H_fcBV6nfY6bLaSlQXHp1mSdTAKxIdsqKcQ2u3qg5bVOiBZ8sZdbUSZgG9FP6oAK1Y=>, which introduced user-based access control (UBAC). UBAC simplifies user collaboration in Snowflake securable objects such as Streamlit applications.

UBAC allows object owners to grant privileges directly to users, streamlining the sharing process and eliminating the need to create or modify roles for every sharing scenario. This is particularly beneficial for sharing limited-audience and under-development assets with specific colleagues.
With UBAC, principals with the permission to grant privileges, will be able to grant privileges directly to users. For example:
(Unset) GRANT USAGE ON STREAMLIT streamlit_db.streamlit_schema.streamlit_app TO USER bob

We understand that this new access control model may affect your governance practices. If you need to disable UBAC in your account after Bundle 2025_02 becomes enabled by default, set the account parameter DISABLE_USER_PRIVILEGE_GRANTS = TRUE

For more information, read the User-based access control private preview documentation <https://go.snowflake.net/MjUyLVJGTy0yMjcAAAGaK51H_FUzCT_KbEOVDHdi7C5OFEuI6a2QPRy6XWGTzhWbTdxUQZrMqsjse3vTLiuxHe9Ogsc=>. This preview topic provides use-case scenarios, FAQs that answer common questions, and further guidance, including
column2: when to use RBAC vs. UBAC, how to monitor UBAC usage, and best practices for integrating UBAC into your existing governance processes.

column1: If you have any questions regarding this change, please open a case <https://go.snowflake.net/MjUyLVJGTy0yMjcAAAGaK51H_D900FAXqc55KDzs5Hxd80fEz186QavSJ52u890ZyE0QBH-A5eufFBxcQG9r_kHWtCY=> with our support team and reference BCR-1924.
To provide the best experience and value to our customers, Snowflake is continually improving and enhancing our

service offerings. As part of these ongoing efforts, changes to existing/established product behavior are sometimes required. Please see our behavior change policy  <https://go.snowflake.net/MjUyLVJGTy0yMjcAAAGaK51H_HyJ1nBt0h-5Z6yTJWJ1KKZLiHWhOx64GV_NAI4Q4j-Ldeej--qlqWyVWswcAlEbQrQ=>to learn more about the process.

# Q: How do I stay spiritual in an increasingly technological world?
I’m sure you’ve either used it, or heard about it. It’s seemingly everywhere, and it feels like it popped up overnight. And because technology advances so rapidly, many of us are disoriented.
It can feel like this big, scary, dark thing. Especially when we haven’t taken the time to shine a light on it.

For us – people who want to live a life of intention — who care about our spirituality, **the question is: what do we do **[**about this mystifying technology?**](https://magic.beehiiv.com/v1/4d03390d-2481-4299-b949-ffd8b38b4c38?email=aicoaching2025@gmail.com&utm_source=jayshetty&redirect_to=https://subscribe.therundown.ai/?form=open&redirect_delay=1&_gl=1*16ao951*_gcl_au*NjUyMzczMjY1LjE3NTI4ODM3MjIuMTk2NjY3Mzg0LjE3NTg3NDI2NjEuMTc1ODc0MjgzNw..*_ga*MTk2YzU4MDctZGFlZi00MjQ3LWIzZDYtYTQ1MTUwMmJiZTQ0*_ga_E6Y4WLQ2EC*czE3NTg4MzkxODgkbzM1NzIkZzEkdDE3NTg4NDE1MTgkajYwJGwwJGgzMzA4OTE5MzM)

A few months ago I had the [privilege of sitting down with the legendary author and guru Deepak Chopra](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=alL6EYL9bm0) to discuss this very topic. Deepak has inspired me for many years, and I take his ideas very seriously.
In this conversation, he likened AI to a knife.
In the hand of the wrong person, it is a weapon that can be used to hurt you. In the hands of a surgeon, it can save your life.
Sure, there are unsavory uses of AI, just like any other tool.

But whether we like it or not, this is a tool that’s here to stay. And so rather than ignore it, the wiser choice is to learn to be just like the surgeon who can [use this tool for good](https://magic.beehiiv.com/v1/4d03390d-2481-4299-b949-ffd8b38b4c38?email=aicoaching2025@gmail.com&utm_source=jayshetty&redirect_to=https://subscribe.therundown.ai/?form=open&redirect_delay=1&_gl=1*16ao951*_gcl_au*NjUyMzczMjY1LjE3NTI4ODM3MjIuMTk2NjY3Mzg0LjE3NTg3NDI2NjEuMTc1ODc0MjgzNw..*_ga*MTk2YzU4MDctZGFlZi00MjQ3LWIzZDYtYTQ1MTUwMmJiZTQ0*_ga_E6Y4WLQ2EC*czE3NTg4MzkxODgkbzM1NzIkZzEkdDE3NTg4NDE1MTgkajYwJGwwJGgzMzA4OTE5MzM).
**What does that look like in the case of spirituality?**

If you just ask AI to talk with you about spirituality, it will give you fairly broad answers. But in my conversation with Deepak, he walked through the process of training AI - whether it was [ChatGPT](https://chatgpt.com/), [Perplexity](https://www.perplexity.ai/), or what have you - to train itself on the ancient texts he was most interested in.
You can actually tell AI, in your prompt, what wisdom to access.

As Deepak was quick to point out, AI will never have consciousness. But what it does have is superintelligence. It can read and find patterns much, much faster than any human can. So if you want it to analyze all the recorded works of Socrates, just ask. If you want it to analyze the Vedas, ask again.

If you’re not sure what to ask _about_, [follow a trusted source like Rundown AI, to get the latest AI news, and understand why it matters](https://magic.beehiiv.com/v1/4d03390d-2481-4299-b949-ffd8b38b4c38?email=aicoaching2025@gmail.com&utm_source=jayshetty&redirect_to=https://subscribe.therundown.ai/?form=open&redirect_delay=1&_gl=1*16ao951*_gcl_au*NjUyMzczMjY1LjE3NTI4ODM3MjIuMTk2NjY3Mzg0LjE3NTg3NDI2NjEuMTc1ODc0MjgzNw..*_ga*MTk2YzU4MDctZGFlZi00MjQ3LWIzZDYtYTQ1MTUwMmJiZTQ0*_ga_E6Y4WLQ2EC*czE3NTg4MzkxODgkbzM1NzIkZzEkdDE3NTg4NDE1MTgkajYwJGwwJGgzMzA4OTE5MzM). Like I do.
In Deepak’s case, he’s able to ask questions like “What did Plato think of this?” or “What did the Buddha think of that?” As a result, his spiritual practice is now enhanced by the tool.

I know this idea may seem kind of outrageous – that we can enhance our spirituality using a modern piece of technology. And by no means am I suggesting that technology should ever replace your inner wisdom. [Relying too much on AI can backfire](https://academic.oup.com/pnasnexus/article/4/10/pgaf316/8303888). And AI can be wrong.
Like all things, it’s a balance.
With intention, these emerging technologies can help you unlock your highest potential.
You’ve built your human circle with care. Now let tech carry some of the weight.

Everyone talks about AI, but no one has the time to learn it. 9/1/2025, 12:02:00 PM,Ali Abdaal,ali@aliabdaal.com,Candace,aicoaching2025@gmail.com,NA,How To Stay Focused - The 90-20 Rule,<5qu5ex8krot7hnm8rr7f6h9k8e444cnh30xrv@convertkit-mail2.com>,"Hey friends,
After a busy few weeks in London, I’ve been trying to settle back
into my “normal” routine here in Hong Kong. I’ve been carving out
some solid deep work blocks to tinker away on upcoming YouTube
video scripts and plan our next course to help people build a
lifestyle business (more on that soon 👀), but I’ve noticed that I
barely make it past mid-morning before I start to lose focus.
I’m ready for a second coffee, hitting the toilet, and scrolling
on Instagram, but then I’m like “hmm, maybe this is just my body
telling me I actually need a break.” It’s not just
procrastination or a lack of willpower or motivation - I’ve just
But what the hell is an ultradian trough? Well, we first need to
understand what’s called an ultradian rhythm.
If you’re someone who tracks their sleep with some sort of
wearable device, you may be familiar with the little graph that
shows when you were in different sleep stages, like light sleep,
Over 50 years ago, a chap called Nathaniel Kleitman discovered
that we move through these different stages of sleep in roughly
90-minute cycles during the night, but Kleitman also found that
our brain and bodies operate in a similar rhythm throughout the
These are your ultradian rhythms - biological oscillations that
occur on cycles less than 24 hours.
So unlike your circadian rhythm, which is your 24-hour internal
body clock that tells you when to sleep and when to wake up,
ultradian rhythms are much shorter and occur many times over a
They look a bit like this:
At the start of the day, we’re full of energy and have lots of
focus. Our brain and bodies then start to burn through our energy
stores, and all the waste from our mental and physical activity
is building up in our system.
We reach what’s called an “ultradian peak” where we’re totally in
the flow, but after about 90 minutes, we start feeling tired,
distracted, and maybe even a bit irritable. You might also feel
hungry, thirsty, need the toilet, stuff like that, and this is
the “ultradian trough” that I mentioned at the start.
While it is possible to push yourself to focus for 3-4 hours or
even sometimes the entire day (which I was totally guilty of back
when I was creating the course material for our $1K Challenge 🫣),
it’s not aligned with our underlying biology.
We need to restore our energy and remove that waste buildup
before we’re able to focus effectively again - yet most of us
overlook this. We work non-stop and find artificial ways to push
through that mid-morning or mid-afternoon slump with things like
But without taking a break, you won’t be as focused, you won’t
enjoy the work you’re doing as much, and over time, you’ll just
head down a road that leads to burnout.
So this is how I build my day of focus around my ultradian cycle,
because let’s face it, productivity is about managing both your
1️⃣ Understand the timings of your ultradian cycle
Step one involves figuring out when you’re most alert after
getting out of bed because that marks the start of your first
For some people - often called “early birds” - this might be
first thing in the morning, but for others, the first ultradian
cycle might start in the afternoon. There’s no right or wrong
2️⃣ Aim to get 2 ultradian cycles of deep work in your day
If you’re someone who wants to get deep work done, aim to get 2
ultradian cycles into your day. Try and also time you cycles so
they work for you - for example, I like to do one cycle in the
morning and one in the afternoon after I’ve been to the gym.
Yes, it is possible to do more than 2 cycles a day, but I’ve
found that my focus in the first and second cycles is far better
than my focus in the third and fourth.
3️⃣ Follow the 90-20 rule (but break it down)
Work for up to 90 minutes and then take a break to relax and
recharge your batteries - 20 minutes is ideal, but any break is
Try and stand up, move away from your desk, grab some water, go
on a quick walk, or just do a bit of stretching. (I keep my yoga
mat permanently rolled out so that it removes the friction to
doing a bit of stretching and it’s worked decently well, although
writing this email has reminded me that I haven’t actually done
Now, you might be wondering: “But Ali, what if I can’t focus for
90 minutes straight?” And that’s totally fine - you just need to
start smaller. This is where my Focused Hour Formula that I teach
Instead of trying to power through 90 minutes of pure focus, I
take five minutes to plan and organise my stuff, fifty minutes to
focus, and five minutes to reflect and recharge. It’s the
framework I use for pretty much all my focus sessions.
But the hour isn’t actually set in stone - sometimes I’ll do one
5-50-5 block within my 90-minute cycle, or I might break it into
2 shorter 25 minute focus sessions with mini-breaks in between.
It really just depends on the task and how I’m feeling that day.
And the goal isn’t to hit some magic number - it’s to find a
structure that works for you to make the most of each ultradian
window. So if you can focus for half an hour, brilliant. If you
can maintain focus for the full 90 minutes and that feels good,
There’s loads more useful stuff inside LifeOS (
) to help you design your time and energy around how your brain
actually works, so if you found this email useful then you might
want to check it out here (
Otherwise, have a great week ahead and hit reply if you try this
approach, I’d love to hear how you get on.

2/11/2025, 2:44:12 PM,Team Ali Abdaal,team@aliabdaal.com,Candace,aicoaching2025@gmail.com,NA,🥳 A Reminder To Celebrate The Small Wins,<n4u4z20wxvavhx8drn5u6h6d4xgggsl@convertkit-mail2.com>,"Hey Candace,
I’ve decided to make a late change to what I was going to write
about this week. Earlier today one of my team shared an Instagram
story with me that I’d posted back in January 2018, celebrating
the fact that I’d finally reached 2500 subscribers.
It seems a little surreal looking back on that now. I was going
through a particularly intense period with my degree and hitting
2500 subs felt like a significant moment in my YouTube journey.
At that time, I was celebrating subscriber growth in increments
of 100 so just going past that 2.5k mark really meant a lot.
Seeing that screenshot reminded me about the importance of
celebrating your wins, regardless of how big or small they might
seem when you’re looking back on your journey.
I’ve seen it with our PTYA (
) students too when they share their wins in the community - from
getting 500 views, passing 1000 subscribers or getting monetised,
all the way to celebrating larger milestones like getting a
silver play button for passing 100k subs.
Each one of these milestones is significant in its own right for
whatever stage of the journey you’ve reached but if you don’t
stop to appreciate them, you’ll quickly lose the enjoyment,
enthusiasm and energy you need to stay consistent on YouTube.
But the thing is - it’s easy to forget to just stop and
It’s easy to reach one milestone then immediately chase the next
one, especially on YouTube where view or subscriber numbers are
And it’s easy to fall into the trap of measuring your success by
these metrics. While metrics have their place, this Instagram
story reminded me that the journey is even more important than
I also wanted to share the screenshot because I know that
sometimes it might be difficult to relate to a larger channel if
you’re just starting out. I get that and I wanted to show that I
was once at the start of the journey, celebrating subscriber
gains in increments of 100 and just focussing on making my videos
1% better every time and gradually improving every week.
And it didn’t take long for things to compound. In fact, it was
only a couple of years after this Instagram story that I passed 1
million subscribers on YouTube (and my celebrations for that
milestone were actually a very similar Instagram photo 😅).
So this week it's just a short reminder to make sure you take the
time to celebrate those wins or milestones regardless of where
you are along the YouTube journey.
Have a great week creating content and I'll speak to you soon.

column1: 4/3/2025, 4:02:34 AM,Ali Abdaal,ali@aliabdaal.com,Candace,aicoaching2025@gmail.com,NA,🎯 The Secret to Writing Hooks That Keep Viewers Watching,<d0ugqd98lob0hokn8o8tmhz8vv544fl@convertkit-mail2.com>,"Hey Candace,
Hope you're having a good day.
It’s that time of year again for us - Quarterly Planning - and
this time, the team are all here with me in Hong Kong 🙌
It's been a productive week and I'll be talking more about our
reflections in this week's issue of my personal newsletter,
LifeNotes, which you can join here (
Anyway, I actually wanted to talk about an area of scripting and
video production that’s still overlooked on YouTube - the hook.
The other day, I was scripting a Book Club video called Watch
This If You Feel Like You’re Behind in Life. It’s about something
called mimetic desire—which Luke Burgis talks about in his book
Wanting—but as I was working on the script for this video, I
And I do this a lot.
In fact, I sometimes write multiple different versions of the
hook before filming a video, and I’ll often record these right at
the end of my filming session when I’ve properly warmed up.
(Incidentally, this idea of filming the hook after you’ve
recorded was a hack I discovered last year after spending hours
trying to get a hook correct before actually getting the video
filmed - it genuinely works, would recommend).
Anyway, as you’d have heard me or other creators talk about in
the past, the first 30 seconds of your video are the most
important part of the content—it’s when a viewer decides to
either stick around and keep watching or click away.
So if there’s one thing worth obsessing over in your videos, it’s
But writing a great hook can be tricky, so I wanted to share a
few essential (and optional) elements to take yours from a level
The first 5-10 seconds of your video should closely align with
the title and thumbnail. If your video’s called The Secret to
Making Money on YouTube, don’t open with a random story about
what you ate for breakfast that morning.
Instead, make sure that content you deliver immediately matches
the promise made in the title and thumbnail. For example you
could say, “Most people fail at making money on YouTube because
they get one crucial thing wrong.”
Give people a reason to trust you, because viewers are more
likely to stick around when they believe you know what you’re
talking about. So if you’re talking about growing a business,
share your experience as a successful entrepreneur.
You’ll notice that I give a similar intro spiel at the start of
most of my videos, and it goes something along the lines of: “Btw
if we haven’t met, hi my name’s Ali, I’m a doctor turned
entrepreneur and author of the New York Times bestseller,
Feel-Good Productivity. Since 2017, I’ve been making videos on
this channel about books, ideas, strategies and tools that help
build a life we love. These days, my main gig is building Sparkle
Studios, where my wife and I are creating a series of
productivity apps we wish existed in the world, like Voicepal (
Give people a reason to keep watching by hinting at the main
payoff—or the main value they’ll get from the video.
Instead of saying, “By the end of this video, you’ll know how to
stop procrastinating,” you could create an open loop: “There’s
one simple mindset shift that completely changed how I approach
productivity—and most people get it wrong.”
This creates a curiosity gap which is an important element in
So those are the staple elements of a great video hook. But
remember, hooks don’t need to be super long and complicated.
If you want to go even further, here are a few extra elements you
could consider including to make it even stronger:
1️⃣ Personal Anecdote – A quick personal story makes your hook
more relatable. So if you’ve struggled with the thing you’re
teaching, definitely share that with your audience. It helps
people connect with you on a deeper level, and they’ll be more
likely to stick around and subscribe.
2️⃣ Input Bias - People value content more when they know how
much time/effort/money went into it. For example, you could say
something like, “I read 10 books on this topic so you don’t have
to” or “I spent a whole week researching this idea, and this is
3️⃣ Target, Transformation, Stakes - This formula was created by
a guy called George Blackman. Fun fact: George started working as
a scriptwriter for me back in the day, and it’s a great framework
to use when writing your hooks (and he’s actually coming to do
some scriptwriting sessions for the PTYA (
* Identify your target audience - Who is this video for? (E.g.,
If you’re someone who struggles to find motivation…”)
* Share their desired transformation - What will they get out of
watching this video? (E.g., “…and you want to finally feel in
* Highlight what’s at stake - What will happen if they don’t
watch this video? (E.g., “…you need to hear this, because
otherwise, you’ll stay stuck in the same cycle forever.”).
As I share with my PTYA (
) students, the best way to get better at something is through
action. It sounds obvious I know, but improvement only comes as a
result of doing the thing, so you’ll only level up your YouTube
hooks if you actually practice writing more of them ✍️
So next time you sit down to script a video, try spending a bit
of extra time on the hook. Use some of the elements from this
email, test out what works with your audience, and don’t be
And if you want to take things a step further, you can learn more
about hooks, scripting and different ways of structuring each
) where we dive deeper into all these areas.
I’d also love to read the hook for any video you’re currently
working on, so please hit reply and share it with me. 😜

In addition to Launch Week 15, here’s everything that happened with Supabase in the last month:
New API Keys + JWT Signing Keys
Supabase now supports JWT signing keys with Supabase Auth.
Analytics Buckets with Apache Iceberg Support

We launched Supabase Analytics Buckets in Private Alpha—storage buckets optimized for analytics with built-in support for Apache Iceberg. We’ve coupled this with the new Supabase Iceberg Wrapper to make it easier for you to query your analytical data.
We’ve unified logs under a single interface in our Dashboard as well as added new capabilities to our AI Assistant to improve the debugging experience.
Build with Figma Make and Supabase
Designers, PMs, and developers can now build fully functional apps, complete with real backend logic using Supabase, without leaving Figma.
10X Larger Supabase Storage Uploads, 3X Cheaper Egress

You can now upload files as large as 500 GB (up from 50 GB), enjoy much cheaper cached egress pricing at $0.03/GB (down from 0.09/GB), and increased egress quota that doubles your egress before you have to start paying.
Edge Functions: Persistent Storage and 97% Faster Boot Times

Edge Functions now support Deno 2.1, persistent file storage so you can mount any S3-compatible storage and read and write to them inside of your functions, up to 97% faster boot times, and support for Deno’s Sync APIs.
Improved Security Controls and a New Home for Security

We launched the foundations of several security features we plan to build on in the upcoming months, including centralized security docs and organization‑wide security settings in the Dashboard. We also published a security roadmap.
You can now spin up, view diffs, and merge your branches directly from the Supabase Dashboard without having to connect to GitHub.
Today we are releasing Platform Kit, new components in the Supabase UI Library that makes it incredibly easy to build platforms on top of Supabase.
Stripe-To-Postgres Sync Engine as an NPM Package

Now you can conveniently sync your Stripe data to your Supabase database by importing the npm package @supabase/stripe-sync-engine, whether in your Node.js app or even deploying it in a Supabase Edge Function.
We’ve been collaborating closely with Algolia to bring you a connector for Supabase so you can easily index your data and enable world class search experiences.
* Security guidelines for using MCP servers. [Docs ( https://supabase.com/docs/guides/getting-started/mcp#security-risks )]
* Supabase MCP Server can now query docs to maintain accuracy in results.

User Created Hook for Supabase Auth. Programmatically inspect and reject user creation requests before they’re inserted into your database. [Twitter ( https://x.com/kiwicopple/status/1940840299686670772 )] [Docs ( https://supabase.com/docs/guides/auth/auth-hooks/before-user-created-hook )]

* New Iceberg and DuckDB Foreign Data Wrappers. [Iceberg ( https://supabase.com/docs/guides/database/extensions/wrappers/iceberg )] [DuckDB ( https://supabase.com/docs/guides/database/extensions/wrappers/duckdb )]
* InterviewForge -Transform any Job Listing into a Personalized Interview [Website ( https://interviewforge.org/ )]
Supamode - The admin panel that transforms your Supabase database into a powerful CMS. [GitHub ( https://github.com/makerkit )] [Website ( https://makerkit.dev/supabase-admin )]
Soshi - Start automating your growth on X today. [Website ( https://app.soshi.io/login )]
* Open Source MVP Boilerplate Template for Production-Ready NextJS+Stripe+Supabase App [GitHub ( https://github.com/ShenSeanChen/launch-mvp-stripe-nextjs-supabase )]
Turn your Supabase into an AI-ready MCP server [GitHub ( https://github.com/vivek100/supaMCPBuilder )] [Website ( https://comforting-baklava-546887.netlify.app/ )]

Garden Genie - Cultivate the green space of your dreams without guesswork. Track your plants, get care instructions, and receive recommendations to help your plants thrive. [Website ( https://gardengenie.lovable.app/ )]
Paul Copplestone - CEO of Supabase, talks about the discipline needed to cross the enterprise chasm without isolating your original community [YouTube ( https://youtu.be/eVJlXHFO8qU?feature=shared )]

9/18/2025, 5:40:30 PM,Peter Diamandis,peter@diamandis.com,NA,aicoaching2025@gmail.com,peter@diamandis.com,Why Entrepreneurship is Safer Than Employment,<1758231377645.27ed4c0c-a9aa-4c0c-903f-04af051a2f11@2973685m.a360.com>,"Read time: 90 sec
Here are five contrarian insights about career safety in 2025 that most people get backwards:

1/ College debt is now riskier than startup equity. The math is simple but brutal: $250k in student loans for a degree that might be obsolete in four years versus equity in a company you control (or co-found). We've reached the tipping point where taking on massive educational debt is the speculative bet, versus starting a company.

The ""safe” (traditional) path requires you to believe that industries won't be disrupted (not true, they all will be), that your specific skills will remain valuable (they will fade rapidly), and that you'll earn enough to service debt that compounds faster than most startups burn cash (hmmm…).

2/ Employment security is an illusion in exponential times. Job security died when the half-life of skills dropped below the half-life of careers. Tech layoffs, AI automation, and economic volatility mean traditional employment now carries hidden risks: you’re betting your entire income stream on decisions made by people who probably don't know you exist, and are focused on quarterly profit reports.

When a VP decides to ""right-size"" or a board chooses to ""pivot,"" employees become accounting entries. As an entrepreneur you may fail, but you'll fail forward with transferable skills and network effects.
3/ The career risk hierarchy has inverted for the first time in history. We're seeing something unprecedented: founding a company has become statistically safer than climbing a corporate ladder.

While massive tech layoffs hit 150,000+ workers in 2023-2024, successful entrepreneurs built lasting value and optionality. The reason is simple: entrepreneurs own their failure modes, employees don't. When you control the variables, you can manage the risk.

4/ Yes, entrepreneurship isn't universally safe - it's just relatively safer (and getting more so over time). The tools to become a coder (Replit, Lovable, Cursor, etc.) are demonetized and democratized. A full entrepreneurial education is available for free on YouTube. Historically, it’s true that 1 in 10 “VC-backed startups succeed” — but increasingly, the ability to code, build, and raise money is growing rapidly.

PLUS, realize that today in 2025, $1B per day is being invested into AI, growing to >$3B per day by 2030. This is the field that is exploding while traditional employment is shrinking. Where would you rather play?

5/ The optimal strategy is asymmetric: limited downside, unlimited upside. Smart career building in 2025 means building antifragile income streams. The new ""safe"" career path isn't employment or entrepreneurship exclusively, it's creating multiple income vectors where failure in one area strengthens your position in others.
This might mean consulting while building products, or freelancing while scaling a service business.

My thesis: act on this dynamic while it lasts. Build now, when the perceived risk is high but the actual risk is low. The best entrepreneurs are emerging from this period precisely because they're contrarian enough to start companies when everyone else thinks it's ""risky.""
By the time entrepreneurship feels safe to the mainstream, the outsized opportunity will diminish. I truly believe the only career path of the future is entrepreneurship.
Bottom line: Get building. The career safety you're looking for exists, but it's the safety of owning your own destiny and your ability to build with AGI (read: god-like tools).
If you’re building something that matters and want to leverage exponential technologies like AI to do it — Abundance360 might be for you.

Happiness isn’t just about how we feel overall. It’s also about
how we experience our daily lives.
It’s one thing to say life is good when reflecting on it as a
whole, but what about the small, everyday moments that make up
the majority of our time? If we break life down into individual
hours and activities, how many of those actually feel worth
Enter The Skip Test - a thought experiment that uncovers how much
of our daily lives we actually want to experience.
In his book What We Owe the Future, philosopher Will MacAskill
describes an experiment where psychologists surveyed 8,500 people
to assess their real-time happiness levels.
Instead of asking general questions about life satisfaction, they
At random times of the day, participants were asked:
👉 What are you doing right now?
👉 How long will this activity last?
👉 If you could, with no negative consequences, would you skip
forward in time to the end of this activity?
The outcome of the activity would be the same. They’d just skip
So if someone was making a cup of tea, they’d blink, and
suddenly, they’d be holding the tea, already made, without
remembering the process of making it.
On average, people chose to skip 40% of their waking hours.
That means nearly 6.5 hours of each day weren’t worth
They wanted the outcome, but they didn’t want to live through the
This raises some pretty deep questions. If a huge portion of our
lives feels skippable, what does that say about how we spend our
When I first heard about this experiment, I immediately asked
myself: How much of my own day would I skip?
Off the top of my head, maybe 30%.
❌ Filming courses – Love teaching, but sometimes the setup and
❌ Writing – Some days are fun, others feel like a grind.
❌ Gym sessions – I love the result, but if I could blink and have
my post-workout muscle ache without actually lifting the weights,
On the other hand, some activities feel intrinsically valuable,
So, if you find yourself wanting to skip too much of your day, it
might be a sign that something needs to change.
Here are three ways to lower your Skip Percentage:
* Work out with friends instead of alone.
* Play music or a podcast while doing mundane tasks.
* Turn everyday activities into a game—track progress, set
* If emails feel like a waste of time, delegate or automate
* If you dread a commute, explore remote work options.
* If a relationship or job feels like something you’d always
skip, it might be time for a bigger change.
* Maybe the deepest fix: reframe how you see ""skippable"" moments.
* Can that boring meeting be a chance to practice patience?
* Can that workout be something to appreciate instead of endure?
Not every experience needs to be thrilling, but maybe we can
learn to find meaning in the process, rather than just chasing
And let me know: How much of your time would you choose to skip?
And what can you change to make your days feel more worth living?

Trump has previously canned scientists, closed databases and otherwise fettered
the delivery of inconvenient facts. Today’s newsletter is about the
administration’s efforts, across the government, to throw out troublesome data
and silence the people who gather it.
Expertise and data can pose problems for any president’s agenda, but Trump has
done more than his predecessors to erase the inconvenient facts.
* Climate science. In the name of deregulation, the Trump administration
rejected the scientific consensus that greenhouse gases threaten public
health. Trump’s budget eliminates funding for a Hawaii lab that has collected
climate data for 70 years. The administration is shuttering the E.P.A.’s
scientific research arm. It also retired an extreme-weather project that
tracked the costs of natural disasters and said it would stop updating a
database that companies use to calculate their emissions.

Now there are fewer people in a position to challenge the White House. Trump has

leader in France, made a particularly controversial one: to deploy
air-conditioners across the country if her party came to power.
Now air-conditioning is political. The head of France’s Green Party said the
country should instead build greener cities and more energy-efficient buildings.
A conservative newspaper defended the technology: “Making our fellow citizens
sweat limits learning, reduces working hours and clogs up hospitals.”

Hi, fellow future and current Data Leaders

Before diving into today’s newsletter, I want to take a moment to thank this issue’s sponsor: Hex [ https://substack.com/redirect/69f00c36-d54e-459b-b905-a7d8e0acc0ae?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. Hex brings the magic of AI to data analysis workflows, whether you’re using code or no-code. Hex helps organizations work together with data and avoid jumping between different data tools for querying, data science, visualization, and spreadsheets. Over 1600 organizations use Hex to do everything from deep analysis to self-serve.
Now let’s jump into the article!
A few months back, I wrote an article about what hasn’t changed in the data world. And much of what hasn’t changed are the problems we face.
Of course, there are also plenty of things that have changed in the data world since I started. For example, the technologies and practices we use.
Even the words and terms we use, although mostly the same, have changed. Whether you like it or not.
When I started, no one used the term analytics engineer, and even the concept of a data engineer was still relatively new(at least in terms of how popular it later became).
In the same way, I have seen plenty of things change. Some of these changes are temporary, I believe (like my first point), others are likely larger trends.
So let’s dive into what’s changed in the data world in the last decade.
1) Everyone Wants Seniors On Their Team

Something strange started to happen a a few years ago. Whenever I was speaking with data leaders and they brought up hiring, they always referenced senior engineer [ https://substack.com/redirect/128fe6ec-c900-4b15-8c31-866acf2ac363?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]s and analysts. That’s the only position they were looking for.
It didn’t really click what was going on until the chart above came out recently…and well things became clear.
Both in terms of anecdotally and in terms of data there is a trend to hire more senior engineers over a mixed team.
I’ve heard a couple of causes:
A senior engineer with a copilot can get far more work done by themselves.
Senior engineers tend to be able to jump into problems faster and apply what they’ve used in the past to solve said problem.

Data teams [ https://substack.com/redirect/02ff01ce-0f2f-43ea-a073-287d1b2980f3?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] are smaller than they were a few years back and in turn they don’t have the head count for juniors.

That last point is from my experience, so it’s anecdotal. But, I think it’s also what many other consultants and data leaders are seeing. Smaller teams, perhaps in response to the considerably larger data teams of the early 2020s.

I do have some friends who are currently working to try to create tools to help junior engineers become more productive even if a senior engineer is around. And I imagine there will be a correction in this trend. Because if you only hire senior engineers, eventually said seniors will just demand more income until it’s no longer viewed as cost effective to mostly hire seniors.
Don’t just take my word for it, feel free to share your own thoughts.
2) Let’s Just Start With The Cloud
It was only a few years ago where the cloud was still an option that companies would consider.

Now I find many companies and data teams jump to the cloud immediately. And those not on the cloud already are migrating. Over the past few years I’ve done over half a dozen SQL Server to Snowflake [ https://substack.com/redirect/9b3485f6-8963-49c0-b148-a5786f01e877?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] migrations. Don’t just take my word for it. Looking at the chart above from Accenture back in 2021 also showed a similar trend of migrating away from on-prem to the cloud for analytics.
Cloud has become the first choice for many companies.

This is true up and down the ladder in terms of company size. Small, large, medium, I haven’t had one project where someone decided to run a database or data pipeline  [ https://substack.com/redirect/ee7e4603-82e8-48e3-9df1-08acd6f3341f?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]locally. Other than to test an idea or via a dev workflow. I know, some of y’all are probably reading this thinking, well, I am still on-prem!
There are still plenty of data stacks on-prem. Some have to be for regulations others find it cost effective to be on-prem.
However, in my experience, I am running into fewer and fewer teams that are relying on an on-prem solution for analytics.
3) Data Teams Don’t Jump To Building Their Own Custom Data Pipeline Solutions

When I first started in the data world, many “data pipeline” systems were built with cron, Windows task scheduler, maybe SQL Server agent as the scheduler, calling either a bash or Python script, or directly calling SQL or SSIS.

Most companies I’d walk into would likely have built their own data pipeline and orchestration solution. Many of which were built over the past decade or so, and you’d literally be able to sense when data leaders [ https://substack.com/redirect/56cd13c3-6025-4c0e-a0b4-d69387d54652?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] changed because the style of how things were written would change.

Instead, there are plenty of other options, especially with the Cloud(again), from as simple as using a Lambda [ https://substack.com/redirect/b8c9c411-58b5-4c32-92a0-1a27e561474a?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and Eventbridge or going straight to a tool like Airflow. People are using pre-built tools to manage their automated pipelines.
I imagine there are many reasons for this:

There is an expectation to deliver actual impact faster. Meaning if you spend time just building a data orchestration system which requires you build logging, meta-data tracking, scheduling and other components before even delivering a data pipeline, you’re likely going to hear it from the business.

There is a lot more intro content out there, and a lot of it starts with tools such as Airflow. So if you’re a new data engineer or looking to set-up your first pipeline for your company, you’ll likely run into it and start there.

Job requirements often ask for tools such as Airflow [ https://substack.com/redirect/6a3cd3c3-b8ff-4741-8251-b29f8c477a43?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], Coalesce [ https://substack.com/redirect/c90d7dc7-e465-401f-9509-eb0d0236cc8e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], dbt [ https://substack.com/redirect/d201572e-afa1-4516-a071-54306d8ff289?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], and so on which means that’s what new data engineers pick-up.
Whatever the reason, building heavily custom data pipeline systems seems to be a less frequent occurrence.
As always, I’d love to hear your thoughts on this as well.
4) No One Is Questioning SQL As The Lingua Franca Of Data Anymore

Alright, that’s not 100% true. There are still people who dislike or want to replace SQL [ https://substack.com/redirect/dfe86030-9ecc-4997-bb9f-05e348e1a251?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. In fact, I usually find that most data engineers fall into liking. Either SQL or Spark(via data frames and Python).
However, had you joined the data world in 2015, every tool seemed to be building its own query language. Some were just offshoots of SQL, like BigQuery’s Legacy SQL, HiveQL, etc.

Other query languages tried to build a completely new approach to how you queried data. And of course, there was NoSQL, which was always touted as “Not Only SQL. But it’s hard for me not to read it as a way of pushing against SQL in both an underhanded/overt way via a name.
Regardless, here we are in 2025, SQL is more popular than ever.

You can check out Luke Barousse [ https://substack.com/redirect/548158fc-0b9d-4bf5-a3a8-efb2c183cb20?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]’s graph above, where he scraped [ https://substack.com/redirect/7889e411-06dd-4d40-aa9a-21ab6bf97375?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] data for job requirements. As you can see, SQL is almost always required. People now start by learning tools that further enforce that, like dbt.
SeattleDataGuy’s Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.

It’s impossible not to acknowledge that AI is playing a role in how data teams work. Whether someone is just adding in an LLM to get rid of having to write DDL [ https://substack.com/redirect/7a08ca25-6383-4e8d-a934-e3420593a736?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] statements, or your IDE has three different copilots running at once. AI is changing the way we work.
On the positive side, I’d say I’ve personally used it and seen it remove a lot of the redundant work I’ve done in the past.

On the more negative side, I’ve also seen people start to rely on it so heavily that they don’t really look into debugging. Even when an error arises, they just put said error back into their copilot and have it try to figure out the problem. Sometimes this works, but many times I’ve seen more and more code bloat get written as a result…I guess we kind of debugged in a similar fashion during the peak of Stack Overflow.
My final thought here is that: I wouldn’t be surprised if some of that feeling of efficiency we get when using an LLM is more similar to just the feeling of movement over progress.

The more things change, the more they stay the same. But things do change. Not overnight. Just because someone in SF released some magic box that makes us all constantly question our own self-worth, doesn’t mean that tomorrow all work will cease.
Just because many of our data workflows are online, we will magically start finding new value from data, no matter how much marketing there is out there.

What I have seen change is the size of companies looking into their data, and the speed at which companies are demanding data to provide them value. Perhaps that’d better be rephrased as the impatience the business has for the data team. This could account for the hiring of seniors and the usage of the cloud, which might be viewed as faster.
But don’t let me be the only one sharing. I’d love to hear your thoughts, what has changed, what has stayed the same?
Feel free to comment, and as always, thanks for reading!

There are thousands of new articles posted daily all over the web! I have spent a lot of time sifting through some of these articles as well as TechCrunch and companies tech blog and wanted to share some of my favorites!
How and Why Netflix Built a Real-Time Distributed Graph: Part 1 — Ingesting and Processing Data Streams at Internet Scale

The Netflix product experience historically consisted of a single core offering: streaming video on demand. Our members logged into the app, browsed, and watched titles such as Stranger Things, Squid Game, and Bridgerton. Although this is still the core of our product, our business has changed significantly over the last few years. For example, we introduced ad-supported plans, live programming events (e.g., Jake Paul vs. Mike Tyson [ https://substack.com/redirect/10507132-94b0-43b8-9482-ac029fd8dd8c?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and NFL Christmas Day Games [ https://substack.com/redirect/a93c46e4-4984-4c5f-bb0e-794a842f1804?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]), and mobile games [ https://substack.com/redirect/86b8dc51-2859-469d-af02-ea7b1a1d9d3a?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] as part of a Netflix subscription. This evolution of our business has created a new class of problems where we have to analyze member interactions with the app across different business verticals. Let’s walk through a simple example scenario…
Is “data-driven” just slowing down your decisions?
For decades, companies have been chasing the idea of being data-driven. I recall when I first started the term was plastered everywhere.
Every blog you read and conference you went to, someone referenced that term along with the idea of data being the new oil.

Everyone wanted to be driven by data. After all, companies like Facebook and Google were doing so well. And not just them, there were plenty of statistics that showed that companies that used data were more profitable than their competitors.
Is It Time to Say Goodbye to Data Engineers?

Ever since tools like SSIS [ https://substack.com/redirect/9b5b168f-0b68-4737-9ed3-11d836257898?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] came onto the scene, vendors and business leaders have been on a mission to remove what they see as the biggest roadblock to data-driven decision-making: data engineers.
Or their counterparts—DBAs, ETL Developers, and Data Architects.
Sure, not everyone says it so explicitly, but you can see it in vendor marketing and in the decisions made by the business.

I remember talking to a veteran data expert who’s been in the field for three decades. They told me that when SSIS [ https://substack.com/redirect/07de3ac4-8970-419b-9a53-f1be336461fb?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] first launched, people were genuinely afraid for their jobs. The idea that you could just drag-and-drop tasks that once required code was nerve-racking. But if you’ve used SSIS, well, you know the truth.

To some extent, I get why the idea is appealing. When a leader requests a report, a software engineer wants to modify an application table, or a data scientist wants to explore a new dataset, who’s the one slowing down the project?

What Does a Data Scientist Do?

Data science professionals — including data analysts and data engineers — build complex, quantitative algorithms to organize and synthesize large amounts of information used to answer questions and drive strategy in their organizations. They communicate these highly technical results and deliver tangible outcomes to various stakeholders.
Leaders in the field must also be proficient in key technical tools and skills, including:
With these advanced technical skills as well as managerial expertise, professionals can advance their data science career and pursue a role with a competitive salary in an increasingly vital field.

The final application deadline is May 14. If you have any questions about the Master of Information and Data Science program or the application process, do not hesitate to contact your Admissions Counselor at 855-678-6437 or slee2@datascience.berkeley.edu

4/8/2025, 9:56:06 AM,Jay Shetty,email@jayshetty.me,NA,aicoaching2025@gmail.com,Jay Shetty <reply@jayshettycoaching.com>,What are your “3 P’s”?,<20250408135606.45b730bbfb7319c3@cio57195.jayshetty.me>,"There’s always a bigger client to chase…
And no matter how successful other people would say you are, you always feel like there’s more you could have done.
If it does, you could be experiencing the “arrival fallacy”.
Because today our society is so focused on tangible goals, that we lose sight of what really fulfills us in life.
1. Purpose - what do you feel called to help with or do? Who do you daydream about being or being more like?

2. Passion - if money was no object, how would you spend your time? So often we get lost chasing money and lose sight of our “why”. We settle for emptiness to tick the money box and end up feeling lost.
3. Process - what can you do today that you couldn’t do before you started - and how can you help others now that you couldn’t do before?
Once you have alignment with these “3 P’s”, your success won’t feel like the end of the road.
But a signpost on a bigger journey.
So as a simple self-reflection exercise…
I’d encourage you to take out your phone or a piece of paper now and write down your “3 P’s”.
Then assess how closely you are living and working in alignment with those.
Later today I’ll tell you why that’s so important - and what next steps you need to take.
So make sure you practice this self-reflection now…
And reply to this email if you’d like to share your “3 P’s” - I’d love to hear more about you.

10/15/2025, 4:50:51 PM,SeattleDataGuy from SeattleDataGuy’s Newsletter,seattledataguy@substack.com,NA,aicoaching2025@gmail.com,SeattleDataGuy from SeattleDataGuy’s Newsletter <reply+2wxe2i&51dsk7&&932abf545d9b858243d6e8220f862ade622920d51d2ef60adecdd42dddaa68e0@mg1.substack.com>,When Words Become Data Architecture,<20251015205051.3.b1d20b2de3874bc5@mg2.substack.com>,"View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/when-words-become-data-architecture
Hi, fellow future and current Data Leaders

Before we dive in, a quick plug for Retool [ https://substack.com/redirect/400d34b7-8549-4a67-9254-d411a2e521a3?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. Their new AI-assisted dev capability lets you build internal tools on top of your live data—without wrangling a prototype or settling for a static BI dashboard. Describe what you need, and Retool creates a secure app you can fully customize. Perfect for building interactive dashboards and admin tools connected to your warehouse, dbt, or orchestration metadata.
Now let’s jump into the article!

It’s the early 1950s, and an American journalist named Edward Hunter begins publishing a series of reports(and eventually books) about U.S. prisoners of war in Korea. He claimed they were being “brainwashed”.

But the term brainwashed up until this point actually didn’t exist in English (or at least wasn’t popularized). [ https://substack.com/redirect/87b962ba-bd56-4d95-9425-6e17840af507?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]

The term caught fire. It appeared in headlines, films, and congressional hearings [ https://substack.com/redirect/87b962ba-bd56-4d95-9425-6e17840af507?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. It’s important to note that Hunter wasn’t merely a journalist
column2: he was a seasoned propaganda expert who had served in the OSS, the predecessor to the CIA.

column1: The U.S. military seized on the idea of “brainwashing” to discredit confessions made by American POWs, including statements admitting to biological warfare. Depending on the source, some claimed that the word “brainwashing” was injected into the English language solely so the military could have a defense against the American POWs who were making said statements.
Now, why am I writing about this?
The Seattle Data Guy who now lives in Denver?

Because many of the words we use in our day-to-day as data engineers and analysts were only created in the past few decades, and yet many of them dictate our choices on tooling, on design, and the work we take on. So I wanted to dig into how the words that we use play that role.
Words Shape the Way We Work

I used brainwashing as an example because it’s a little dramatic, and it shows how language can shape how we see the world, how it can excuse behavior or choices because we now have a word to define it. But not every term is born from manipulation. Sometimes, we’re just trying to name something new we’ve noticed, like a pattern or behavior.

And when you do it well, when you manage to wrap something complex into a simple phrase, the word will spread. It creates a shared language. It makes it easier for others to build on your thinking and to bring structure to what was previously vague.

So I don’t view this as inherently bad or negative. But it can limit our perspective on the world. These words and terms are also often self-replicating, passed from one company or organization to another long after their meaning has drifted.
It All Started With The Data Warehouse
It’s hard not to start this dive into terms that have shaped the data world without mentioning data warehousing. It remains a central part of our work today.

It’s why you’re stuck on the migration [ https://substack.com/redirect/9ce4bff0-aee1-462c-8612-bc0141dc7a7c?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] project from SQL Server to Snowflake [ https://substack.com/redirect/67cd1cc0-8231-4c30-9c2f-361f0a598d97?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
It’s why everything seems to revolve around lakes and lake houses. It’s all merely an evolution or variation of that term. There might be a better approach, but why question it?

I’d be remiss not to reference the Data Lakehouse. I think you could argue that this one concept alone(and Databricks [ https://substack.com/redirect/86942708-bc34-494d-9653-2804e182d637?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] putting everything they could behind it) willed Databricks into the spotlight as more than just a managed Spark service, even though it has been difficult to shake that label even to this day.

It’s funny because Databricks wasn’t even the first company to use the term [ https://substack.com/redirect/cee97c15-2846-4658-8da7-b82bfdf1200d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. But Databricks did everything they could to legitimize the term even further. The first article around the topic was around January 2020 [ https://substack.com/redirect/4abc3979-6d14-48de-8bd8-20f46e6b6fc7?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], and then somewhere in early 2021, the idea took off(see Google Trends below).

Again, I do think this was capturing an idea that had already been floating around. It seemed like a natural combination of Data Warehouse and Data Lake, which is why I believe the idea was so potent.
We were tired of having to build both.

Snowflake was likely very aware that this term gave Databricks a new mental road in people’s minds. This was an opportunity for Databricks to start taking workloads from Snowflake. Thus, much of Snowflake’s marketing opted for the term “Data Cloud”.

In fact, I recall a video I recorded with a Snowflake employee that was never aired. I mentioned Snowflake as a data warehouse, but the employee insisted I re-record it and never let that video see the light of day.
Personally, I think Data Cloud lacks a certain level of graspability. It really is meaningless.
If you’re creating a term, it needs to capture your audience effectively. If it’s so broad that it could literally mean anything(as I believe data cloud does), it probably won’t catch on.
Some words and concepts last for decades.
Others barely make it a decade.

When I first started in the data world, various vendors were pitching schema-on-read [ https://substack.com/redirect/d4163f4c-d012-4a70-9b09-ce4dfe3506c0?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], and not too long after that, the term Modern Data Stack came around.

Perhaps one of these terms was created with limited longevity in mind. [ https://substack.com/redirect/a7fd49e5-90b9-4a3e-b3cf-536806ca53c5?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] I say that mostly in jest. I think most companies have no idea what terminology will stick. Maybe that’s why Databricks keeps trying to invent new terms [ https://substack.com/redirect/a4065a4e-d633-4b8d-93df-e70d7f6fac18?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].

But like some viruses, a population might slowly become inoculated to an idea. Perhaps due to overexposure or due to the vaccine of reality, people start to question it. Break it down and push it aside. Once enough of a population has rejected an idea, it slowly ceases to exist.

That’s what has seemed to happen to both schema-on-read and now Modern Data Stack. Well, for many, the idea of the MDS passed away a while back [ https://substack.com/redirect/6f9cceed-cd56-4ff1-8153-0d4ab1d3dd83?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
SeattleDataGuy’s Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
I write this article both for myself and for everyone reading. The terms we use in the data world are useful and can help us have a shared language.
They can also trap us in our current world, where we limit our ability to see beyond the walls of our own minds.
Those ideas can be hijacked by vendors to sell their products.
They can also play naturally in a space that was always looking to be better defined.
We’ve had so many terms floated in the past few years that it can feel overwhelming.
And I bet that shortly we’ll have some new terms that redefine an all-in-one data stack coming out real soon.
If you’re just getting started in your data career, I owe you an article with a longer breakdown of all the terms and their timeline almost like a vaccine to ideas.
Upcoming Data Events I’ll Be At
Queries, Cocktails & Community - Small Data SF Happy Hour [ https://substack.com/redirect/7f49d898-13fb-4e3e-9969-26d24f73828d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]

There are thousands of new articles posted daily all over the web! I have spent a lot of time sifting through some of these articles as well as TechCrunch and companies tech blog and wanted to share some of my favorites!

I’m entirely convinced that basically every developer alive today heard the adage “dress for the job you want, not the job you have” and figured that, since they always wear jeans and a t-shirt anyway, they might as well apply it to their systems’ architecture. This explains why the stack of every single company I’ve seen is invariably AWS/GCP with at least thirty microservices (how else will you keep the code tidy?), a distributed datastore that charges per query but whose reads depend on how long it’s been since the last write, a convoluted orchestrator to make sure that you never know which actual computer your code runs on, autoscaling so random midnight breakages ensure you don’t get too complacent with your sleep schedule, and exactly two customers (well, potential customers).
If You’re New to Data, Read This Before You Build Anything
When you’re just getting started in data, everything feels exciting, and everything sounds like a good idea.
“Oh, this process takes ten minutes? I’ll automate it with VBA!”
Fast-forward four weeks, and you’re trying to meet the finance team’s expectations, reconciling numbers, and banging your head against a table, wondering why you ever volunteered.
New paradigms show up with shiny names and polished diagrams. They sound smart. You’ve got nothing to compare them to, so you try them. After all, everyone else seems to be.

That’s what this article is about: the things I wish I understood earlier in my data career. It started because there were so many buzzwords and new products popping up in the past few weeks, it might not be clear what’s actually going on if you’re new to the data space.
Whether you’re early in your data career or just want a sanity check, here’s a breakdown of the stuff that actually matters (and the fluff that doesn’t).

If you enjoyed it, consider liking, sharing and helping this newsletter grow.

1/21/2025, 4:03:11 PM,Team Ali Abdaal,team@aliabdaal.com,Candace,aicoaching2025@gmail.com,NA,⛵️ A Reminder To Enjoy The Journey,<p9ugxvrl5nb9h2376g4hqhpz49033hr@convertkit-mail2.com>,"Hey Candace,
Hope you’ve had a good start to the week :)
I had a few people reply to my email last week resonating with
the difficulty around getting back into the flow of filming at
the start of the year - trust me, it’s something we all struggle
with, regardless of the size of the channel 😅
But it is something I’ve been thinking about quite a bit this
week too, or more specifically, remembering why it’s important to
If you’ve followed my content for a while, you’ll know I’m a big
fan of journey before destination as a framework for thinking
about everything really - it’s such a succinct but powerful way
of illustrating the relative importance of focussing on the
process, rather than fixating on the outcome.
And even though it’s ‘nice’ to see a 1 out of 10 on a video (like
we did today), that's an outcome and I know that’s not a
sustainable way of really getting joy from the process of
creating videos. After all, if you’re not enjoying it, you’re
going to struggle to create content consistently.
It reminds me of a question from one of the experiments in my
book which is ‘what would this look like if it were fun?’
In the book I’m not talking about YouTube and it might seem
strange to bring it up because, in theory, it shouldn’t really
apply here where we're choosing to create content and so it
should be something that we enjoy.
But that doesn’t mean that there aren’t parts of the video
production process that you simply find difficult, dull or boring
or perhaps moments along your YouTube journey where you’re just
struggling to find the motivation, like I was last week 👀. And
it’s in those moments where asking the question of ‘what would
this look like if it were fun?’ can still be immensely helpful.
And I actually asked myself a variation of this when I was
setting my target for the channel that I mentioned last week
(getting back to 2 videos per week on a consistent basis).
Essentially, what would make this easier, more enjoyable and, as
a result, more likely to happen? 😅
For me, the solution I settled on was reintroducing a weekly
(rather than monthly) YouTube idea generation session with 2-3
team members which we’d dropped last year but which we’ve
reinstated at the start of January and so far the results have
been great. The sessions have been creative, effective and, above
In fact, the video released earlier today (
) was actually the first one to come out of those ideation
sessions and it was a 1 out of 10 immediately so the process is
clearly working - not just with helping me stay consistent but
So I’d encourage you to think about ways that you can make each
part of the video production process more enjoyable. Perhaps
you’re like me and you enjoy working with others or you get more
joy from gamifying the process - whatever it is, just remember to
keep it front of mind if you’re struggling with motivating
yourself to start or grow your channel as we kickstart 2025.
Hope this has helped and have a great rest of the week :)

Hi BDEs! This one might be a little controversial… but I’ll see you in the comments 🥊😂 btw i asked my bff Chat to make me an image of 2 data analysts fighting and i can’t believe it made them both men despite knowing I AM A WOMAN!! ok… ⬇️
Useless SQL Concepts you’ll NEVER use IRL 🤫
There’s a weird disconnect between how SQL is taught in courses and what you actually use in real life…

Sometimes you take a course (or more likely, see a LinkedIn post) and they hit you with pretty niche SQL skills. Recursive CTEs. Natural joins. Theoretical stuff you’ll prob never use… but hey, they look impressive 😏
And then you get your first real job as a data analyst and realize…
Nobody is asking for any of that. Not one single person !!!

Finance bros are not asking recursive problems LOL, they just want their revenue numbers. Most everyday business problems have simple-ish solutions as long as you have ✨accurate and clean✨ data to support them.
A quick customer order count by region
A dashboard that shows revenue by week
Why do these two reports say different things?
So let’s talk about the SQL stuff I thought I’d be using daily but haven’t touched outside of a course, LinkedIn post, or technical interview.

Disclaimer: These skills of course have their use cases. I am not saying they should NEVER be used or are NEVER needed. But… in general, I think they’re overhyped considering the amount they’re used. Wanted to get that out of the way before the data engineer bros with quick fingers come at me 😏

They’re cool in theory especially if you want to do some heavier duty programming (come at me, SWEs 😉) but never have I ever had a bro from sales ask me business problem requiring this complexity… They can be useful if you’re working on recursive hierarchies, but 99.999% of the business questions I’ve solved didn’t require recursion. I think they’re great to learn and expand your skills, but you probably won’t use them very often to solve everyday business questions.
JOIN employee_hierarchy eh ON e.manager_id = eh.employee_id

They’re fancy but just a gimmick. Why are we letting SQL guess and assume what keys to join on because we're lazy? Not only is not specifying your joining keys super lazy (if I didn’t already make that clear before), but it also opens up a lot of possibility for error. In the real world, column names aren’t always consistent, self-explanatory, and clean. This can make natural joins a ✨blindfolded join✨. Plus, who wants to decipher this while reviewing your code?! Just don’t.
-- let SQL make assumptions and decide how to join
If you’re ready to level up in SQL: build your first Data Analytics project in only 30 min for free (even if you’re a complete newbie with no experience):

No one actually uses right joins because they’re not useful. Only data psychos use them. (ok fine, I use them once in a blue moon when I accidentally put my tables in the wrong order and I'm too lazy to switch them... but NEVER for a production query). In my Intermediate SQL course [ https://substack.com/redirect/68097474-c92a-4553-9885-3b67973a7d63?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]🔗, I only spend 3 minutes teaching them, and I spend the whole time making fun of them and undermining them. As they should be ✌️
-- if you accidentally put the wrong table on the left side... you can switch your left join to a right join instead of moving the tables 😂

Nothing will ruin your optimization and explode your data warehouse like accidentally doing one of these bad boys when you don’t mean to. They can be useful for generating dummy data or creating all the combinations on purpose, but 99.999% of the time I’ve seen a CROSS JOIN in the wild, it was because someone forgot a join condition. And that someone might’ve been me a few times… 🤫 OOPS!

BUT I think I’m going to stop throwing shade at cross joins and write about the actual use cases for next week’s newsletter. Are they the MOST important or useful SQL skill? Absolutely not. But they do have good use cases which I’ll show some love to next week!

Ah yes, the fancy and less useful cousins of ROW_NUMBER(). I’m sure I’ll get hate for this one… Listen, I LOVE a good window function. But in the real world? I'm not usually handling multi-tiered tiebreakers. I’m just trying to get a top 1 product per user. Or most recent transaction. Or best performing ad. And for those types of business problems? ROW_NUMBER() is good enough 99% of the time. BUT I will say that it’s 100% worth learning the different ranking functions and their calculations because you most likely will see them in technical interviews. It’s one of the most common interview questions, so study all 3!
DENSE_RANK() OVER (ORDER BY revenue DESC) AS dense_rank,
RANK() OVER (ORDER BY revenue DESC) AS rank,
ROW_NUMBER() OVER (ORDER BY revenue DESC) AS row_number

Writing SQL that’s fast, accurate, AND solves the right problem with the least amount of complexity. Sure, there are times you may need dense_rank() or recursive CTEs in the real world. Maybe even a cross join— there’s a time and a place for everything.

But my advice? Skip the edge cases, and focus on the 20% that drives 80% of your work. Learn what actually moves the needle, transforms data efficiently, and is easy to maintain longterm. That has the biggest impact in business.
✅ That’s what makes you the go-to data person everyone trusts.
Get GOOD at the fundamentals—and you'll be unstoppable.

Row_Number() vs. Rank() vs. Dense_Rank() Easily Explained!
A lot of business problems rely on ranking methods in SQL:
Most recent order data per customer

And the list goes on! More often than not, I’m looking for the most recent or first of something which requires a rank number of 1 (either in descending or ascending ranking order), but sometimes I need a different rank number like for question #3 above. And 9 times out of 10, Row_Number() suffices for a quick rank because I don’t usually care too much about ties, but sometimes you do have to consider tie handling which requires rank() and dense_rank(). Regardless of how little I use these compared to Row_Number(), it’s really good to understand the differences in these calculations because this is one of the most common SQL interview questions.
Seriously, interviewers LOVE asking about the differences between these, so you better know them well and be able to explain them!!

Let’s start with Row_Number() since it’s the easiest to understand and the most widely-used. Row number provides a unique sequential number to each row and doesn’t account for ties/duplicates. It doesn’t repeat or skip any ranking numbers, and it’s non-deterministic, which means that you might not always get the exact same result since it arbitrarily handles ties. Check out the query and output below which ranks Taylor Swift songs on the 1989 album by danceability (rounded to 1 decimal place) descending, which means that the most (rounded) danceable songs will be at the top.
row_number() over(/*partition by Album*/ order by           Danceability_rounded desc) as danceability_rownumber
Even though there are ties for the rounded danceable score, each song has its own unique row number. Notice how the ties (0.8) are completely ignored.

Also note that I have commented out partition by Album for simplicity. This is not needed since I filtered the query for the album 1989 and there’s only 1 album. If I removed the 1989 album filter and wanted to repeat this ranking process for each album, then I would use the partition by inside the window function before the order by to specify how to segment the data for the calculation (by album!).

Now let’s see how Rank() is different. Rank() ranks each row in the dataset and allows for ties with duplicates. After a tie, it skips to the next row number, so the list of numbers will have gaps and won’t be complete if there are ties. Notice how all of the 0.8 rounded danceability scores are all tied for a rank value of 1, and then the next rank number after that is 5 to account for the 4 above it in ranking.
rank() over(/*partition by Album*/ order by Danceability_rounded desc) as danceability_rank

Now for dense_rank()… it’s ALMOST like rank() except it doesn’t leave rank number gaps by skipping to the next row number after ties/dups. Dense_rank() uses the next rank number in the sequence after a tie. See the 0.8 values tied for 1 below? Then after that is 2 for the next rank value? This is how dense_rank() and rank() differ.
dense_rank() over(/*partition by Album*/ order by Danceability_rounded desc) as danceability_denserank
I personally think it’s easiest to understand them all when they’re in the same query and output side by side.
Apologies for the ugly copy and paste below. Find the commas to see the different rows in the code!! And copy and paste this into an IDE to clean it up.
row_number() over(/*partition by Album*/ order by Danceability_rounded desc) as danceability_rownumber,
rank() over(/*partition by Album*/ order by Danceability_rounded desc) as danceability_rank,
dense_rank() over(/*partition by Album*/ order by Danceability_rounded desc) as danceability_denserank
Knowing how to rank well in SQL is a MUST, but knowing how to explain the differences between row_number(), rank(), and dense_rank() are even more important when it comes to interviews.

Why brands are drawing the line: The case for illustration

Illustration, a medium once sidelined by photography and now challenged by AI, is reasserting itself in the design world. From large-scale murals to branded world-building, creative teams are rediscovering the power of drawing to spark emotion, break from visual sameness, and build ownable identities. But illustration isn’t always an easy sell. Illustrators, art buyers, and agency leads talk about the risks, rewards, and real reasons behind the illustration’s comeback
column2: and why now might be its most exciting moment yet.

column1: * Pour-over packaging: Inside the plastic-free design behind the Dwell Dripper
* Mascots, mood & minimalism: The bite-sized branding of Hank’s Bagelry
* Check out this week's featured designers!
The return of the brushstroke: Why illustration is reclaiming space in design

In an era of overused stock imagery and AI-powered sameness, illustration is making a calculated comeback in branding and advertising. From the walls of Selfridges to Nike’s hand-painted murals, brands are turning to illustrators for storytelling that stretches beyond what photography can deliver. Illustration offers emotional depth, flexibility, tactility, and immediate distinction, all of which are increasingly valuable in saturated markets. But it’s still often seen as “risky,” “childlike,” or too slow for tight timelines.

Agencies are referencing procurement hurdles, budget misconceptions, and the assumption that AI can replicate human illustrators. But experts argue that when briefed and budgeted right, illustration can be lean, fast, and unforgettable. As more brands seek world-building and expressive identities, illustration is evolving into a multidisciplinary superpower with applications in motion graphics to immersive experiences. It’s becoming a potent design tool for those ready to invest in something more unexpected, handcrafted, and emotionally resonant.
Fast, effective research for busy designers

In this workshop, you’ll see how Lyssna makes it easy for busy designers to run quick, impactful studies, gather real feedback, and back up design decisions. You’ll learn practical methods that fit into your workflow, helping you make better design decisions without the time, resources, or buy-in usually needed for big research efforts.
How Zenpack brewed up the perfect package for Verve's Dwell Dripper
Pour-over perfection doesn’t just come from the beans
column2: it starts with smart design. When Verve Coffee Roasters launched their first brewing device, they wanted packaging that would feel just as intentional. Enter Zenpack. Tasked with creating a plastic-free, retail-ready container that protects, displays, and delights, the result was a fold-flat, handle-equipped structure that feels more like product design than packaging. Learn about crafting the award-winning Dwell Dripper experience, from the dieline to the shelf.

Hank’s Bagelry bakes up a brand with just the right amount of whimsy

Not every bakery brand needs a manifesto. Sometimes, it just needs a vibe… and a great mascot. For Hank’s Bagelry, Studio Ongarato embraced a less-is-more approach, crafting an identity system rooted in personality and play. Anchored by a delightfully nostalgic character (hello, Mr. Men!) and a grown-up serif, the rebrand balances charm and clarity. With locations in Melbourne and Perth and ambitions to grow, Hank’s hits the sweet spot between childlike joy and strategic simplicity. This is branding with BIG breakfast energy.

Subqueries can be used in the FROM clause if you need to calculate something first and then pull from that result. For example, since you can’t nest aggregate functions in SQL, you have to calculate them in 2 separate SELECT statements—using either a CTE or subquery for the first calculation and then the final select statement to nest the second calculation around the first one. Here’s an example with a subquery where we’ll find the maximum average temperature per month:

First, the average temperature per month is calculated in the inner (or sub) query. Then the max of the avg_temp column is taken to calculate the max of the monthly averages. Remember we can’t do nested aggreate functions like max(avg(temperature)) in SQL! We have to use a subquery… or CTE! See the same query written with a CTE below:

Either method is fine, but I’d recommend a CTE if the query gets any longer or more complex because it’s easier to understand. In my opinion, this use case of subqueries (in the FROM clause) looks the most similar to CTEs— just inside out. So this may be a good place to start if you want to learn about them.
You can also JOIN subqueries as well like this:

Personally, I’d start to use a CTE here though instead of a subquery because it’s beginning to get a little complex to unravel, especially if you pass the code off to someone else to review. There’s no harm in using a CTE to have more legible code! If you can’t tell, I’m Team CTE most of the time🤩

Christianity has a branding problem. Over the past 25 years, tens of millions of
